        "h": "Frequently Asked Questions",
        "p": "Frequently Asked Questions regarding encircled signatures often revolve around the nuances of this specific stroke and its immediate impact on daily life.\n\nQ1: Does having an encircled signature always mean I am an introvert or socially awkward?\nA: Not necessarily. While an encircled signature often correlates with introverted tendencies and a need for privacy, many highly sociable and extroverted individuals also use this stroke. In their case, the circle represents a strict boundary between their vibrant public persona and their private, inner self. They may be the life of the party, but they rarely let anyone see their true vulnerabilities. The circle acts as a protective mask rather than a sign of social awkwardness.\n\nQ2: What if I only circle my first name but leave my surname outside the loop?\nA: In graphology, the first name represents your personal identity, ego, and private life, while the surname represents your family, heritage, and social standing. If you only encircle your first name, it indicates that you are fiercely protective of your personal space and innermost thoughts, yet you are comfortable allowing your family or professional persona to interact freely with the world. It shows a compartmentalization where you keep your true self hidden while offering a more accessible version of yourself to the public.\n\nQ3: Is it considered bad luck to circle your signature?\nA: Graphology and numerology do not deal in arbitrary concepts of \"bad luck.\" Instead, they focus on energetic alignment and psychological patterns. An encircled signature is not inherently \"bad,\" but it is restrictive. It creates a closed energetic loop that can block new opportunities, financial abundance, and expansive relationships from entering your life. By keeping everything out, you inadvertently block the good along with the bad, which can manifest as stagnation or missed opportunities rather than luck.\n\nQ4: How long does it take to see changes in my personality or circumstances after I stop circling my signature?\nA: Graphotherapy works by creating new neural pathways in the brain through repetitive, conscious physical action. Generally, it takes about 21 to 30 days of consistent, daily practice of your new, un-encircled signature for the subconscious mind to begin internalizing the change. You may start feeling more open, less anxious, and more receptive to others within a few weeks, with significant shifts in your external circumstances following shortly after."
